## 🟡 Medium Blockers

### 6. `Navbar` — Scroll Handler Without Throttle

**File:** [Navbar.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/portfolio/Navbar.tsx#L48-L56)

**Problem:** `window.addEventListener("scroll", handleScroll)` fires on **every scroll tick** (~60 times/sec during scroll). The handler computes `window.scrollY` comparisons and conditionally calls `setScrolled` and `setActiveSection`.

**Fix:** Add `{ passive: true }` flag AND use RAF-throttle:
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  let ticking = false;
  const handleScroll = () => {
    if (ticking) return;
    ticking = true;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      const isScrolled = window.scrollY > 20;
      setScrolled((prev) => (prev !== isScrolled ? isScrolled : prev));
      if (window.scrollY < 100) {
        setActiveSection((prev) => (prev !== "" ? "" : prev));
      }
      ticking = false;
    });
  };
  window.addEventListener("scroll", handleScroll, { passive: true });
  return () => window.removeEventListener("scroll", handleScroll);
}, []);
```

---

### 7. `SkillsSection` — Re-computing `searchStatus` on Every Keystroke

**File:** [SkillsSection.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/portfolio/SkillsSection.tsx#L529-L541)

**Problem:** `searchStatus` depends on `searchQuery` (not debounced), so it re-computes **on every keystroke**, iterating the entire skills array with `.filter()` and `.toLowerCase()` comparisons.

**Fix:** Make `searchStatus` depend on `debouncedQuery` instead, or compute it inline from `filteredSearch`:
```tsx
const searchStatus = useMemo(() => {
  if (!debouncedQuery.trim()) return "idle";
  return filteredSearch.length > 0 ? "found" : "not_found";
}, [debouncedQuery, filteredSearch]);
```

This eliminates the redundant `.filter()` on every keystroke. The 300ms debounce already handles the visual feedback.

---

### 8. `SmoothScrollProvider` — Lenis RAF Without GSAP Ticker Integration

**File:** [SmoothScrollProvider.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/SmoothScrollProvider.tsx#L31-L36)

**Problem:** Lenis runs its own `requestAnimationFrame` loop (`raf → lenis.raf → requestAnimationFrame`), *separate from* GSAP's internal ticker. This means two independent RAF loops are competing for the same frame budget. When both fire in the same frame, they can exceed the 16ms budget and cause frame drops.

**Fix:** Use GSAP's ticker to drive Lenis (single RAF loop):
```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const lenis = new Lenis({ ... });
  lenis.on("scroll", ScrollTrigger.update);
  
  // Drive Lenis through GSAP's ticker — single RAF loop
  gsap.ticker.add((time) => {
    lenis.raf(time * 1000); // GSAP ticker uses seconds, Lenis expects ms
  });
  gsap.ticker.lagSmoothing(0); // Prevent GSAP from throttling on lag
  
  return () => {
    lenis.destroy();
    gsap.ticker.remove(lenis.raf);
    ScrollTrigger.getAll().forEach((st) => st.kill());
  };
}, []);
```

> **Impact: Eliminates duplicate RAF loop — one of the primary causes of scroll jank**

---

### 9. `ProjectSlider` — Blur Filter on Side Cards

**File:** [ProjectSlider.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/Projects/ProjectSlider.tsx#L308-L325)

**Problem:** Each side card renders a **120% oversized image with `filter: blur(17px) saturate(180%) brightness(1.1)`**. CSS `blur()` is extremely expensive — it forces the browser to rasterize the oversized image and apply a Gaussian blur on every composite. With 2 side cards visible, this is 2× the cost.

**Fix:** Pre-blur the thumbnails at build time (ideal), or use a much smaller resolution for the blur source + `will-change: filter`:
```tsx
// Reduce the blur source to a tiny image
<img
  src={project.thumbnail}
  alt=""
  className="w-full h-full object-cover object-top"
  // Load a much smaller version for the blur layer
  sizes="100px"
  loading="lazy"
  draggable={false}
/>
```

Or better — add `transform: translateZ(0)` (already there as `scale(1.25)`) and ensure `will-change: filter` is set so the blur is GPU-composited:
```css
style={{
  opacity: isCenter ? 0 : 1,
  filter: `blur(${isMobile ? 10 : 17}px) saturate(180%) brightness(1.1)`,
  transform: "scale(1.25) translateZ(0)",
  willChange: "filter, opacity",
  /* containment prevents blur from leaking into layout calculations */
  contain: "strict",
}}
```

---

### 10. `FeatureCardRow` — `projectColorMap` and `projectNameMap` Rebuilt Every Render

**File:** [FeatureCardRow.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/Projects/FeatureCardRow.tsx#L49-L56)

**Problem:** Two `Map` objects are constructed from arrays **on every render** (not memoized). When the auto-slide timer fires every 5s or during drag events, these maps are rebuilt unnecessarily.

**Fix:**
```tsx
const projectColorMap = useMemo(() => {
  const map = new Map<string, string>();
  projects.forEach((p, i) => {
    map.set(p._id || p.id, PROJECT_COLORS[i % PROJECT_COLORS.length]);
  });
  return map;
}, [projects]);

const projectNameMap = useMemo(() => {
  const map = new Map<string, string>();
  projects.forEach((p) => {
    map.set(p._id || p.id, p.title);
  });
  return map;
}, [projects]);
```

---

### 11. `ContributionHeatmap` — 365+ HeatmapCells Rendered at Once

**File:** [ContributionHeatmap.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/portfolio/GitHub/ContributionHeatmap.tsx#L141-L153)

**Problem:** Renders **~52 weeks × 7 days = ~364 `HeatmapCell` components** at once. Each cell has its own hover handlers. When scrolling through the heatmap, the browser must composite 364+ absolutely positioned elements.

**Fix:** This is lower priority since heatmap cells are tiny divs, but you can:
- Memoize `HeatmapCell` with `React.memo` 
- Use CSS `:hover` instead of JS `onMouseEnter/onMouseLeave` for the basic hover state
- Add `contain: content` to the heatmap container

---

### 12. `ActivityHeatmap` — `motion.div` with `whileInView` for ~112 Cells

**File:** [ActivityHeatmap.tsx](file:///home/rocky/Projects/portfolio/components/portfolio/ProblemSolving/ActivityHeatmap.tsx#L84-L112)

**Problem:** Each of the ~112 cells (16 weeks × 7 days) is a `motion.div` with `whileInView` + `whileHover`. Framer Motion creates an IntersectionObserver **per element** with `whileInView`, which is 112 observers for what should be a single visibility check.

**Fix:** Check visibility at the parent level and animate children with CSS:
```tsx
const containerRef = useRef(null);
const isInView = useInView(containerRef, { once: true });

// Then in JSX:
<div ref={containerRef} className="grid grid-rows-7 gap-[3px]" style={{ gridAutoFlow: 'column' }}>
  {cells.map((cell, idx) => (
    <div
      key={idx}
      className={`group relative w-3 h-3 rounded-[2px] transition-all duration-300 hover:scale-125 hover:z-10 ${
        cell.count === 0 ? "bg-secondary/20" : ""
      }`}
      style={{
        backgroundColor: cell.count !== 0 ? accentColor : undefined,
        opacity: isInView ? (cell.count === 0 ? 1 : cell.intensity) : 0,
        transform: isInView ? 'scale(1)' : 'scale(0.5)',
        transitionDelay: `${Math.floor(idx / 7) * 20}ms`,
      }}
    >
      {/* tooltip */}
    </div>
  ))}
</div>
```

This reduces 112 IntersectionObservers → 1 and 112 `motion.div` → 112 plain `div`.

